Real gangsters reserved raw violence for their direct opposite competitors — the police, he said. 

“However, in all instances that we engaged the police in violence, we always suffered more damage than we could mete out,” he said, adding “you do not engage in force and win.” 

“During our times, gangs operated in a distinct way where they exercised self-censorship in enforcing their dos and don’ts.” 

Githenji, who together with Kiriamiti robbed banks, petrol stations and wealthy families in Nairobi, Nakuru and Mombasa counties, said: “We were organised thieves whose agenda was to make money but not terrorise the society. In fact, it was frowned upon for any gang member to rob the common mwananchi. We only targeted companies and the obscenely rich.” 

“We knew that such targets insured their cash and even if we robbed them, their covers would in the long run compensate them.” 



