He lamented that “today thugs act as if in competition to not only impoverish, but also maim and murder even the very old and the very young.” 

Adhered to tradition 

Kiriamiti said the gangs of old used to adhere to tradition, which forbade women, children and the elderly going to war. 

“The only brutal force we used to execute in our robberies was to point guns at people, fire into the roofs and ceilings to make it crystal clear that what we had were not toys and order our victims to lie down with faces pressed on the ground.” 

Substance abuse 

Githenji blames the brutality in today’s gangs to substance abuse. 

“We took our criminal occupations like any other job … We respected what we did and we retained a touch of humanity for our victims. We had an imagination that those we robbed, if given a chance to escape our ordeals with minimum trauma they would go back to making more money for our future hits,” he said. 

Kiriamiti added: “We never went about robbing while high on drugs or on alcohol, rather, we would plan while sober, revisit our plans while sober too and strike while under no influence.” 

Alcohol was only imbibed after a successful heist. 



